  "sections": [
    {
      "heading": "Symptoms",
      "content": "Cervical cancer may present in early stages as asymptomatic or with subtle symptoms such as watery vaginal discharge, postcoital bleeding, or intermittent spotting, which are often not recognized by the patient. As the disease advances, symptoms can include pelvic pain, leg edema, weight loss, anorexia, and persistent coughing. On examination, a visible or palpable cervical mass, ulceration, or barrel-shaped cervix may be noted. For advanced stages, involvement of adjacent organs (e.g., bladder, rectum) can cause hematuria, dysuria, rectal bleeding, or constipation."
    }
